         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">This is the left part of a leaf with the string hole.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="lingcomment"><hi>ṣkas</hi> may be part of a deminutive in <hi>-ṣk(e)</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>yaiṃ</hi> could also be <hi>yeṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">After <hi>tsa</hi> there is maybe a <hi>[ry]</hi>, but there is also something below.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="lingcomment"><hi>ntalyci</hi> is the end of an adjective made to an l-stem, such as <hi>mantalyci</hi> 'irritated'.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment">After <hi>tsaksi</hi> there is probably <hi>[mu]</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="lingcomment"><hi>sälpeñcän</hi> does not inflect like a normal participle; Obl.pl. as epithet of <hi>yok</hi> and <hi>wesko</hi> is probably an oblique dual of a form of <hi>sälpe<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>*</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">The beginning could perhaps be <hi>kura-yknesa</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">The vowel before <hi>·tse</hi> is <hi>a</hi> or <hi>o</hi>. <hi>pe</hi> could also be <hi>ṣe</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
